Adjust rack to top position and preheat #oven{} to 450 degrees. Bring @butter{2%tbsp} to room temperature.

In a #large bowl{}, combine @marinara{14%oz cup}, @cream sauce base{4%oz}, half the @garlic powder{1%tsp} (you'll use the rest later), half the @Italian seasoning{1%tbsp} (all for 4), @sugar{1/2%tsp} (1 tsp for 4), and @salt{}; stir until smooth.

> TIP: Cut top off cream sauce base carton to open fully; transfer contents, using a spoon or spatula to scrape sauce from carton sides.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @panko breadcrumbs{1/2%cup}, @Parmesan cheese{1/4%cup}, a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%tsp}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

Break up @gnocchi{8.8%oz} with your hands, then divide between #oven-ready aluminum trays{2}.

Break up @Italian chicken sausage mix{9%oz} into 1-inch pieces (around 1 TBSP each); divide between trays. Pour sauce over to coat, then evenly sprinkle with panko topping.

Bake on top rack until gnocchi is tender, sausage is cooked through, sauce is bubbly, and panko topping is golden brown, ~{15-18%minutes}.

> TIP: For a more deeply browned crust, broil 2-3 minutes more.

== Garlic Bread ==

While gnocchi bakes, halve @demi-baguette{1}. Spread cut sides with softened @butter{2%tbsp}. 

> TIP: If butter isn't yet softened, transfer to a microwave-safe bowl; microwave for 5 seconds.

Sprinkle buttered sides with remaining garlic powder, @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

When gnocchi has ~{5%minutes} left, place bread cut sides up directly on an #oven rack{} until toasted, ~{3-5%minutes}.

== Serving ==

Once gnocchi bake is done, let sit at room temperature until sauce has cooled slightly, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Meanwhile, halve garlic bread on a diagonal. Sprinkle gnocchi bake with @?chili flakes{1%tsp} to taste.

Divide between plates and serve with garlic bread on the side for dipping.